		{
			"id": "EF5OynGr",
			"type": "text",
			"x": -4734.539248511897,
			"y": 2652.4325615564876,
			"width": 1493.911376953125,
			"height": 595,
			"angle": 0,
			"strokeColor": "#e03131",
			"backgroundColor": "transparent",
			"fillStyle": "solid",
			"strokeWidth": 2,
			"strokeStyle": "solid",
			"roughness": 1,
			"opacity": 100,
			"groupIds": [],
			"frameId": null,
			"index": "b3O",
			"roundness": null,
			"seed": 731270815,
			"version": 2162,
			"versionNonce": 1746276602,
			"isDeleted": false,
			"boundElements": [],
			"updated": 1764882386300,
			"link": null,
			"locked": false,
			"text": "Antes das promises, com o uso facade functions assincronas como setTimeout, por conta da\ncallback function ser puxada para a callback queue, não é possivel retornar ou atribuir o valor de uma\nvariável em contexto síncrono, pois a callbck queue só é chamada quando o contexto sincrono\nestiver sido totalmente executado, então ficamos presos em um setTimeout por exemplo\ncriando nested timeouts em cima dele mesmo, pra termos acesso\n\nnot neceseraly a promise will be called first them something that is on the callback queue, it depends\non the time that the promise was completed. the then method is sync, and it will attach the function \ninto the onfullfilled array, but it will only executing when the promise is finished. If the promise wasnt\nfinmished, there's nothing in the microtask queue yet, but the timeout is, if we put 0 milliseconds for example\n. Its a race condition\nWhen attaching a callback function in the onFullfilled property to be called after\nthe promise is completed, it needs to keep track of the referenced data that existed\nor exists in the outer scope, that's is possible by relying on closures.\nThe response data will be available even before the callback function execution on the micro\ntask queue, but that data is locked and cannot be accessed, but it is on the javascript memory\n",
			"fontSize": 28,
			"fontFamily": 5,
			"textAlign": "left",
			"verticalAlign": "top",
			"containerId": null,
			"originalText": "Antes das promises, com o uso facade functions assincronas como setTimeout, por conta da\ncallback function ser puxada para a callback queue, não é possivel retornar ou atribuir o valor de uma\nvariável em contexto síncrono, pois a callbck queue só é chamada quando o contexto sincrono\nestiver sido totalmente executado, então ficamos presos em um setTimeout por exemplo\ncriando nested timeouts em cima dele mesmo, pra termos acesso\n\nnot neceseraly a promise will be called first them something that is on the callback queue, it depends\non the time that the promise was completed. the then method is sync, and it will attach the function \ninto the onfullfilled array, but it will only executing when the promise is finished. If the promise wasnt\nfinmished, there's nothing in the microtask queue yet, but the timeout is, if we put 0 milliseconds for example\n. Its a race condition\nWhen attaching a callback function in the onFullfilled property to be called after\nthe promise is completed, it needs to keep track of the referenced data that existed\nor exists in the outer scope, that's is possible by relying on closures.\nThe response data will be available even before the callback function execution on the micro\ntask queue, but that data is locked and cannot be accessed, but it is on the javascript memory\n",
			"autoResize": true,
			"lineHeight": 1.25,
			"rawText": "Antes das promises, com o uso facade functions assincronas como setTimeout, por conta da\ncallback function ser puxada para a callback queue, não é possivel retornar ou atribuir o valor de uma\nvariável em contexto síncrono, pois a callbck queue só é chamada quando o contexto sincrono\nestiver sido totalmente executado, então ficamos presos em um setTimeout por exemplo\ncriando nested timeouts em cima dele mesmo, pra termos acesso\n\nnot neceseraly a promise will be called first them something that is on the callback queue, it depends\non the time that the promise was completed. the then method is sync, and it will attach the function \ninto the onfullfilled array, but it will only executing when the promise is finished. If the promise wasnt\nfinmished, there's nothing in the microtask queue yet, but the timeout is, if we put 0 milliseconds for example\n. Its a race condition\nWhen attaching a callback function in the onFullfilled property to be called after\nthe promise is completed, it needs to keep track of the referenced data that existed\nor exists in the outer scope, that's is possible by relying on closures.\nThe response data will be available even before the callback function execution on the micro\ntask queue, but that data is locked and cannot be accessed, but it is on the javascript memory\n",
			"hasTextLink": false
		},
